ype":"LAST","meanings":["Anglo-Saxon: Eten, a giant."],"variants":[{"name":"Eaton","meanings":["English: habitational name from any of various places called Eaton or Eton, such as Eaton Socon (Bedfordshire), Eaton (Cheshire), or Eton (Buckinghamshire), named from either Old English <i>ēa</i> ‘river’ or <i>ēg</i> ‘island, low-lying land’ + <i>tūn</i> ‘enclosure, settlement’.","History: Nathaneal Eaton, born in Coventry, England, <i>c.</i> 1609, came to MA in 1637 and was the first head of Harvard College, in 1638–39."]}]},{"name":"Manley","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English: habitational name from any of the places in Devon and Cheshire, named in Old English as ‘common wood or clearing’, from <i>(ge)mǣne</i> ‘common, shared’ + <i>lēah</i> ‘woodland clearing’. The surname is still chiefly found in the regions around these villages.","English: nickname from Middle English<i>mannly</i> ‘manly, virile, brave’ (Old English<i>mannlīc</i>, originally ‘man-like’).","Irish (County Cork): Anglicized form of <b>Ó Máinle</b> (and often pronounced <i>Mauly</i>), of unexplained etymology. Compare   Malley  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Munley","meanings":["Irish: variant of   Manley  . This surname is rare in Britain and Ireland, and is found mainly in eastern Scotland."]},{"name":"Malley","meanings":["Irish: variant of   O'Malley  .","English (of Norman origin): habitational name from any of several places in northern France called Mailly (Marne, Somme, and elsewhere).","Americanized form of Rusyn (from Slovakia) <b>Mlej</b> (see   Malay  )."]},{"name":"McMonagle","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Irish Cahal.","Irish: Anglicized form of Gaelic <b>Mac Maonghaile</b>, a patronymic from the personal name <i>Maonghal</i>, composed of the elements <i>maoin</i> ‘wealth’ + <i>gal</i> ‘valor’. In this form the consonant cluster <i>-ngh-</i> has been ‘delenited’. Compare   Manley   4, which is based on an earlier form of the genitive."]},{"name":"Minkley","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  German Arno.","English (East Midlands): perhaps a variant of   Manley   with intrusive <i>-k-</i>.","Possibly also an Americanized form of German   Minkler  ."]},{"name":"Munnelly","meanings":["Irish (Mayo): variant of   Manley  ."]},{"name":"Manly","meanings":["English and Irish: variant of   Manley  ."]}]},{"name":"Elen","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["form of   Helen  , now also used outside Wales. It is identical with the Welsh vocabulary word <i>elen</i> ‘nymph’, but this is unlikely to be the origin. It is found in Welsh texts from an early period as an equivalent of <i>Helen</i>, for example as the name of the mother of Constantine, finder of the True Cross."],"variants":[{"name":"Elin","meanings":["Variant spelling of   Elen ."]}]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705197,"age":63,"year":"1455","julianDay":2252488,"title":"Wars of the Roses","description":"Wars of the Roses was a series of English civil wars for control of the throne of England between the royal families House of Lancaster and the House of York. The name of the war was derived as the red rose was the symbol of the Lancastrians and the white rose was the symbol of the Yorks.","url":"https://www.history.com/topics/british-history/wars-of-the-roses","urlTitle":"History - Wars of the Roses","jurisdictionLevel":1}],"lifeSummary":"Elen De Eton Manley was born about 1392, in Cheshire, England as the daughter of John Eaton. She married John de Eaton in Cheshire, England."},"et":{"about 1392–":"umbes 1392–Surnud","1392–Female":"1392–Surnud","1390–1443":"1390–1443","1416–1458":"1416–1458","1357–Male":"1357–Surnud","about 1392":"umbes 1392","1458":"1458","1357":"1357","1455":"1455","1443":"1443","1392":"1392","1390":"1390","1416":"1416","Cheshire, England":"Cheshire, England","Eaton, Cheshire, England":"Eaton, Cheshire, Engla